  "is_vocab": false,
  "stimulus_html": "<p>South American Incas chewed the leaves of the coca bush, <i>Erythroxylon coca,</i> to combat fatigue. Chemical studies of <i>Erythroxylon coca</i> by Friedrich Wöhler in 1862 resulted in the discovery of <i>cocaine,</i> C<sub>17</sub>H<sub>21</sub>NO<sub>4</sub>, as the active component. Basic hydrolysis of cocaine leads to methanol, benzoic acid, and another compound called <i>ecgonine,</i> C<sub>9</sub>H<sub>15</sub>NO<sub>3</sub>. Oxidation of ecgonine with CrO<sub>3</sub> yields a keto acid that readily loses CO<sub>2</sub> on heating, giving tropinone.</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down-30\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBa3NZIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--b93d5b663419dcd152464895ac242cf152c9fad4/OChem_22_EC_047.jpg\" alt=\"A chair conformation of tropinone in which an N C H 3 group bridges from C3 to C6 of a cycloheptanone ring.\">",
